<P>The lieutenant fraught with this piece of intel|ligence,
watched for an opportunity, and as &s;oon
as he perceived the commodore's features a little
unbended from that ferocious contraction they had
&s;uffered &s;o long, ventured to inform him that
Pickle's &s;i&s;ter lay at the point of death, and that
&s;he had left him a thou&s;and pounds in her will.
This piece of news overwhelmed him with con|fu&s;ion,
and Mr. Hatchway imputing his &s;ilence
to remor&s;e, re&s;olved to take advantage of that
favourable moment, and coun&s;elled him to go
and vi&s;it the poor young woman, who was dying
for love of him. But his admonition happened
to be &s;omewhat un&s;ea&s;onable; for Trunnion no
&s;ooner heard him mention the cau&s;e of her di&s;or|der
