a principal &s;ufferer by the di&s;appointment. The&s;e,
however, were no other than the &s;ugge&s;tions of
<PB N="77" REF="85">
temporary di&s;gu&s;ts, that commonly &s;ub&s;ided as
&s;uddenly as they aro&s;e, and never gave the lea&s;t
di&s;turbance to the per&s;on who in&s;pired them, be|cau&s;e
