thought it now high time to make applica|tion;
and therefore by little and little altered his
behaviour from the indifference he had put on, to
<PB N="87" REF="95">
the appearance of more regard and attention.
This produced a favourable change in the boy,
who&s;e eyes &s;parkled with &s;atisfaction one day,
when his ma&s;ter expre&s;&s;ed him&s;elf with a &s;hew of
&s;urprize in the&s;e words, &startq;So, Perry! I find you
don't want genius, when you think proper to u&s;e
it.&endq; Such encomiums kindled the &s;pirit of emu|lation
