return by Winche&s;ter, where he hoped to meet
with &s;ome hints of intelligence, by which he
might profit in his future &s;earch, he &s;truck off
the common road, to take the benefit of a nearer
cut; and finding himself benighted near a vil|lage,
took up his lodging at the fir&s;t inn to which
his hor&s;e directed him. Having be&s;poke &s;ome|thing
for &s;upper, and retired to his chamber,
where he amu&s;ed him&s;elf with a pipe, he heard
<PB N="156" REF="164">
a confu&s;ed noi&s;e of ru&s;tic jollity, which being all
of a &s;udden interrupted, after a &s;hort pau&s;e his
