might never ri&s;e up in judgment again&s;t him.</P>
<P>Having taken this wi&s;e &s;tep, he went in que&s;t
of his &s;cribe, to whom he communicated his bu|&s;ine&s;s,
and promi&s;ed a full-pot by way of gratifi|cation.
The clerk, who was al&s;o &s;chool-ma&s;ter,
proud of an opportunity to di&s;tingui&s;h his talents,
readily undertook the ta&s;k; and repairing with
